Using coordinated observations in the foreshock and the magnetosphere, Wang et al. (2018c) found direct evidence of Pc 5 field line resonances driven by the foreshock cavity. ULF waves excited in the magnetosphere have a frequency similar to that of the foreshock pressure pulses. The toroidal modes are consistent with the shear Alfvénic FLRs, while poloidal modes are also present. A pair of traveling convection vortices and auroral brightening were generated in the ionosphere correspondingly. Recent 3D global-scale hybrid simulations of Shi et al. (2021) assuming a radial IMF illustrated for the first time the properties of self-consistently generated field line resonances through direct mode conversion in magnetospheric response to the foreshock disturbances. It was found that the foreshock wave spectrum covers a wide frequency range and matches the band of FLR harmonics. The fundamental harmonic of field line resonances dominates and has the strongest wave power, and the wave power decreases with the harmonic order. The eigenstructures of the harmonic modes along dipole-like field lines were obtained. The power of the toroidal Alfvén waves is steady under the steady solar wind inputs, suggesting that the FLRs are part of the steady-state magnetosphere. At the equator, an alternating feature of toroidal Alfvén wave components Er\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
